{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638425","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638425"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:53:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:53:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17708"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17708","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17708"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10422"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72018"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10422"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17708"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57488"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"10435"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24333"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24336"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72018","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72018"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe retina processes visual information through multiple cell layers before sending signals to the brain via the optic nerve.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the response of retinal ganglion cells to light stimulation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["ON-centre cells only respond to red light while OFF-centre cells respond to green light","Ganglion cells respond only to movement and not to stationary light stimuli","Both ON and OFF-centre cells respond equally to light anywhere in their receptive field","ON-centre cells increase firing to centre illumination while OFF-centre cells decrease firing to centre illumination","All ganglion cells increase firing in response to light"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ERetinal ganglion cells have circular receptive fields with centre-surround organisation. \u003Cstrong\u003EON-centre cells increase firing when light hits the centre of their receptive field\u003C/strong\u003E while being inhibited by light in the surround. Conversely, OFF-centre cells are inhibited by light in the centre and excited by light in the surround.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAll ganglion cells increase firing in response to light\u003C/strong\u003E - Different types of ganglion cells have distinct responses to light, with ON and OFF cells showing opposite patterns of activation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBoth ON and OFF-centre cells respond equally to light anywhere in their receptive field\u003C/strong\u003E - The response depends on whether light strikes the centre or surround region of the receptive field, with opposite effects in each area.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EON-centre cells only respond to red light while OFF-centre cells respond to green light\u003C/strong\u003E - The ON/OFF classification is independent of colour processing, which involves different pathways in the retina.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGanglion cells respond only to movement and not to stationary light stimuli\u003C/strong\u003E - While some specialised ganglion cells detect movement, many respond robustly to stationary light stimuli.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis centre-surround organisation allows ganglion cells to detect contrast boundaries and enhance edge detection in visual processing.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Retinal ganglion cells are the output neurons of the retina that form the optic nerve.","ON-centre ganglion cells increase firing when light hits the centre of their receptive field.","OFF-centre ganglion cells increase firing when light hits the surround of their receptive field."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57488"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17708"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57488","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57488"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T21:10:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T21:10:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10422"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72018"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name